{
  "proposals": {
    "1": {
      "objections": [
        {
          "claim": "The proposed `isInternal = !hasInbound` switch does not cover the mixed-batch case this pipeline already creates. `index.js` batches all claimed events for one conversation into a single `runTurn()` call, and `runTurn()` injects internal turns into the same prompt even when an inbound message is present. In that case `hasInbound` stays true, so the internal event still runs on the chat model and full tool loop.",
          "evidence": "`index.js:73-111` groups events by conversation and passes the whole `claimed` array to `runTurn()`. `hook-communication.js:117-119` computes `hasInbound` for the batch, while `hook-communication.js:127-147` still renders internal turns into `[AGENT UPDATES]`. The proposal's `isInternal = !hasInbound` therefore leaves mixed inbound+internal batches on the expensive path.",
          "falsifiable_test": "Queue one `inbound_message` and one `session_complete` for the same conversation in the same deferred drain. If the patched code still resolves the chat model or allows the full multi-round loop for that combined batch, this objection is confirmed."
        },
        {
          "claim": "Changing exhausted internal turns from `held` to `discarded` can silently delete deferred human-facing messages. Due outbox items are replayed as `source: \"internal\"`, so one non-terminal tool call followed by round exhaustion would now discard the outbox item instead of keeping it retryable.",
          "evidence": "`index.js:137-160` replays due outbox items as a turn with `source: \"internal\"`. `hook-communication.js:242-244` is the fallback the proposal changes to `discarded` for internal turns. `index.js:161-162` deletes the outbox KV entry whenever `runTurn()` returns `discarded`.",
          "falsifiable_test": "Create a due outbox item, stub the model to make one `kv_query` call and then produce no terminal tool call within the allowed round. If the patched system deletes the outbox entry instead of keeping it for another attempt, this objection holds."
        },
        {
          "claim": "Reducing internal comms to one round does not actually guard the session budget against the first expensive call. `runTurn()` still invokes `K.callLLM()` without a `budgetCap`, and `kernel.callLLM()` only checks whether the budget is already exhausted before the call starts.",
          "evidence": "`hook-communication.js:175-183` calls `K.callLLM()` with no `budgetCap`. `kernel.js:1473-1475` rejects only when `this.sessionCost >= costLimit`; it does not estimate the next call's cost. So an internal event can still consume the last remaining session budget in its first and only round.",
          "falsifiable_test": "Run an internal comm turn when the remaining session budget is lower than the cost of one LLM call. If the patched code still starts that call instead of short-circuiting before it, this objection is confirmed."
        }
      ]
    },
    "2": {
      "objections": [
        {
          "claim": "A one-line 'do not write experience:*' addition would leave the reflect prompt internally contradictory. The same `kv_operations` section currently tells the model that `experience:*` is writable from session reflect, so cheaper models would still see explicit permission to do the thing the new line forbids.",
          "evidence": "`prompts/reflect.md:110-116` says `kv_operations` are for writing memory and explicitly lists `experience:*` under 'Writable from session reflect'. Adding the proposal's one-line prohibition without removing or rewriting that clause creates conflicting instructions in the same prompt.",
          "falsifiable_test": "Patch only the proposed prohibition into `prompts/reflect.md`, keep the existing writable-list sentence, and rerun session reflect on the failing snapshot multiple times. If the model still emits `experience:*` operations at a non-trivial rate, this objection is confirmed."
        },
        {
          "claim": "Prompt-only guidance does not actually create the 'role boundary' the proposal claims. The runtime still executes schema-valid `experience:*` writes from session reflect, because `executeReflect()` applies `output.kv_operations` and `kvWriteGated('reflect')` allows new or unprotected agent-tier keys.",
          "evidence": "`reflect.js:245-258` loops over `output.kv_operations` and calls `K.kvWriteGated(op, 'reflect')`. `kernel.js:653-660` then permits direct writes to new or unprotected agent keys, which includes `experience:*`.",
          "falsifiable_test": "After making only the proposed prompt change, feed `executeReflect()` a schema-valid `experience:test` `put`. If the key is still written successfully, this objection is confirmed."
        },
        {
          "claim": "Option 1 does not fix the actual rejection behavior in the code path. The reflect-side schema gate uses truthiness (`!op.value?.[f]`) instead of the `undefined/null` check used by the act-side writer, so a structurally present field like `salience: 0` is still rejected as 'missing' even if the prompt shows the right schema.",
          "evidence": "`reflect.js:249-253` computes `missing` with `!op.value?.[f]`. `userspace.js:803-805` uses `=== undefined || === null` for the same required fields. That inconsistency means prompt guidance alone cannot make session reflect writes reliably pass the gate.",
          "falsifiable_test": "Send session reflect output with `kv_operations:[{ \"op\":\"put\", \"key\":\"experience:test\", \"value\": { \"observation\":\"x\", \"desire_alignment\": { \"top_positive\": [], \"top_negative\": [], \"affinity_magnitude\": 0 }, \"pattern_delta\": { \"sigma\": 0, \"scores\": [] }, \"salience\": 0 } }]`. If `reflect.js` rejects it as schema-missing, this objection holds."
        }
      ]
    },
    "3": {
      "objections": [
        {
          "claim": "The proposal's core premise is already false in current code: experience records do persist sigma today, under `pattern_delta.sigma`, and the experience-selection path already reads that field.",
          "evidence": "`userspace.js:272-284` returns `{ sigma: evalResult.sigma, scores }` from `derivePatternDelta()`, and `userspace.js:771` stores that object in `experienceRecord.pattern_delta`. `memory.js:61-64` then falls back to `exp.pattern_delta?.sigma` when scoring experiences.",
          "falsifiable_test": "Write a normal experience through `writeMemory()` and inspect the stored KV record or run `selectExperiences()` on it. If `pattern_delta.sigma` is absent or the selector does not read it, this objection is false."
        },
        {
          "claim": "The exact code snippet in the proposal is not actually valid at the cited write site. Inside `writeMemory()`, there is no local `sigma` variable in scope; the available value is `evalResult.sigma`.",
          "evidence": "`userspace.js:672-815` shows the write block. The function references `evalResult.sigma` at `userspace.js:715`, `userspace.js:811`, and `userspace.js:813`, but there is no `const sigma = ...` before the proposed `experienceRecord.surprise = sigma;` line.",
          "falsifiable_test": "Apply the proposal literally as written and run the experience-write path. If it throws `ReferenceError: sigma is not defined` or writes `undefined`, this objection is confirmed."
        },
        {
          "claim": "Patching only `writeMemory()` does not make the proposal's 'all future experiences will carry surprise data' claim true. Crash experiences are written through a separate code path that never touches `writeMemory()`.",
          "evidence": "`userspace.js:819-850` writes crash memories directly with `K.kvWriteSafe('experience:...')`, including `pattern_delta: { sigma: 1, scores: [] }` but no top-level `surprise` field.",
          "falsifiable_test": "Apply only the proposed `writeMemory()` change, then trigger the crash-memory path. If the resulting crash `experience:*` record still lacks a top-level `surprise` field, this objection is confirmed."
        }
      ]
    }
  }
}
